This is a game like mafia, not an RP. Not an RP. A game. Just say you want in.

The Mission

There are five people. Three are humans. Two are aliens. The humans goal is to complete the mission. The alien's goal is to stall it five times.

*The humans can only communicate in thread. The aliens can communicate in thread and in a private PM I will set up.
*Each day there will be an election for captain.
*Once a captain has received two votes, they can vote for themselves. This confirms them as captain.
*The captain can at any time declare a mission among them and two of their supporters. If they have two supporters, Declare is all you need. If you have more, Declare Name 1, Name 2.
*If the mission is all humans the humans win.
*If the mission contains one or more aliens, the mission will fail and it passes to the next day.
*There are five days.
*The captain loses captainship upon losing majority support(supporters changing their votes or withdrawing votes) or the day passing(failed mission).
*If you are inactive and do not post within 24 hours, I will prod you. 24 hours after that I replace with anyone willing. Posting within this time resets the counter.

Sign up by posting in the thread. First five people.

I'd also point out, for what it's worth, that the psychological strategy is mostly reverse-psychology. Let me explain:

"I know I'm definitely human!"

Every player has incentive to make this claim. The claim is meaningless, and should be disregarded by all other players. Not only that, it's actually a weakness, which I exploited to discredit Syvaris in the last game, even after he had correctly identified the alien team on day 3. Syvaris consistently refused to consider any possibilities that included himself as an alien. I did the opposite. This made me appear more objective and therefore trustworthy. Then I cashed in on that trust in the end-game, when I finally did claim to be human. My claim seemed more credible at that time because I had previously avoided demonstrating subjective bias.

Of course, reverse-psychology is multi-layered and tends to lead one in circles... If everyone takes the above assumptions to be true, then there might be strategic incentive to do the opposite, or the opposite of the opposite, and so on... This makes it a very interesting game.

This game is an example of hypergeometric probability distribution. Scroll down to the section of that article titled "Application and example" and read it carefully. I used that formula to calculate the probability of success on a single mission under the new rules to be 1 in 14, or approximately 7.14%. (I'll show my full calculation in the next post.) A fair game would give each team a 50% chance to win. That's why there are seven missions remaining: 7 * 1/14 = 50%.

I have disregarded the previous two missions as invalid, although the elimination of two possible alien teams does give the humans a slight advantage, but not enough to be substantially unfair. Under the new rules, you can eliminate four possibilities per mission. 4 * 7 = 28. With the previous 2, that's 30 out of 56 possibilities that can be eliminated before the game is over, giving the humans a 53.5% chance to win.

[8356287]

No, I already know what everyone's roles are.

Now for the calculation of the probability of success on a single mission. This gets ugly. Bear with me, or take my word for it.

If you're not familiar with Combinatoric notation, you may find this page to be helpful. Knowledge of basic algebra is assumed, including factorials.

I will use the following notation to represent a combination:

C(n, r) = n! / ((n-r)! * r!)

That is, the function C represents the number of possible combinations of r items chosen from among n total items.

In a hypergeometric distribution, the probability of success is given by the formula:

p = C(K, k) * C(N-K, n-k) / C(N, n)

N is the total number of players
K is the number of humans
n is the number of team-members on each mission
k is the number of mission members that must be human for the mission to succeed.

(Full work will be shown in my next post.)

= 120 / (1 * 24)
= 5

C(N-K, n-k)
= (8-5)! / (((8-5) - (4-4))! * (4-4)!)
= 3! / (3! * 0!)
= 6 / (6 * 1)
= 1

C(N, n)
= 8! / ((8-4)! * 4!)
= 40320 / (24 * 24)
= 70

Returning to the hypergeometric formula:

p = 5 * 1 / 70
= 1 / 14
= 0.071428...
= ~7.14%
